1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:29,952
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodasa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

2
00:00:34,152 --> 00:00:39,076
I thought I'd start with a quote from a nun, Meichi Kyao.

3
00:00:39,396 --> 00:00:40,637
Has anybody come across her?

4
00:00:40,938 --> 00:00:41,679
Meichi Kyao.

5
00:00:42,939 --> 00:00:43,780
She's a...

6
00:00:43,860 --> 00:00:44,741
I don't know if you can see that.

7
00:00:46,122 --> 00:00:46,643
There she is.

8
00:00:50,106 --> 00:00:52,308
There she is, Meichi Kyao.

9
00:00:52,329 --> 00:01:00,957
So she's a Thai nun, died in 91 and was recognized as a fully awakened being, an Arahant.

10
00:01:01,277 --> 00:01:03,719
Her teacher was...

11
00:01:03,886 --> 00:01:06,118
Ajahn Mahabua, perhaps you know him.

12
00:01:06,802 --> 00:01:07,606
Somebody come across him?

13
00:01:07,808 --> 00:01:08,412
No?

14
00:01:08,813 --> 00:01:37,891
there we are okay well this is what she says and i'm just using this as a beginning and then i thought we'd run through the dependent origination which spurs off into various teachings and and then reread this again and you'll see um what a clear statement it is of what it is to live live in the world having liberated yourself um

15
00:01:42,209 --> 00:01:48,055
She, well, she started off by doing a lot of concentration meditation.

16
00:01:48,075 --> 00:01:57,284
And when she went to work with Mahabua, Ajahn Mahabua, she wouldn't take his instructions because he was trying to get her to do vipassana.

17
00:01:57,865 --> 00:01:58,686
So he kicked her out.

18
00:01:59,367 --> 00:02:01,310
And that sort of woke her up a bit.

19
00:02:02,030 --> 00:02:10,038
And having been somewhat humiliated, a little bit of a humiliation, she came back and fully realized the path.

20
00:02:10,019 --> 00:02:12,342
So she was on a learning curve.

21
00:02:13,645 --> 00:02:15,067
So this is what she says anyway.

22
00:02:16,269 --> 00:02:20,917
Mind, body and essence are all distinct and separate realities.

23
00:02:22,639 --> 00:02:24,323
Absolutely everything is known.

24
00:02:25,144 --> 00:02:30,953
Earth, water, fire and wind, body, feeling, memory, thought and consciousness.

25
00:02:32,155 --> 00:02:36,802
Sound, sight, smells, taste, touches and emotions.

26
00:02:37,829 --> 00:02:40,831
Anger, greed, and delusion, all are known.

27
00:02:41,451 --> 00:02:45,975
I know them all as they exist in their own natural states.

28
00:02:47,337 --> 00:02:57,187
But no matter how much I'm exposed to them, I'm unable to detect even an instant when they have any power over my heart.

29
00:02:58,407 --> 00:03:01,050
They arise and cease, they're forever changing.

30
00:03:02,010 --> 00:03:06,435
But the presence that knows them never changes for an instant.

31
00:03:06,989 --> 00:03:09,991
It says forever unborn and undying.

32
00:03:10,634 --> 00:03:12,729
This is the end of all suffering.

33
00:03:14,092 --> 00:03:22,185
Now, the reason I quoted that, you'll see from the way I talk about dependent origination.

34
00:03:23,486 --> 00:03:34,323
So what happened once the Buddha was liberated, there's all sorts of stories as to what teaching came to mind, how he worked it out.

35
00:03:34,423 --> 00:03:42,294
The first watch of the night, he went through dependent origination one way, and the second watch he came the other way, and on the third watch,

36
00:03:42,275 --> 00:03:47,961
He went both ways and then he did that with the Four Noble Truths and so on and so forth.

37
00:03:48,823 --> 00:03:58,254
The interesting thing is that once he had had this cataclysmic insight into human nature, it wasn't as though he knew everything.

38
00:03:58,594 --> 00:03:59,796
It had to be explained.

39
00:03:59,836 --> 00:04:06,645
He had to go through to try and make sense of what he'd actually seen.

40
00:04:06,877 --> 00:04:23,821
And the experience of nibbana, if you want to look at it from the point of view of self, the collapse of self, which is the underlying delusion, of course, begs the question, well, how did I get there?

41
00:04:24,841 --> 00:04:27,326
And that's where this dependent origination comes in.

42
00:04:27,365 --> 00:04:33,814
So dependent origination means, of course, that everything is dependent on something else for it to arise.

43
00:04:34,355 --> 00:04:36,278
Nothing arises of its own accord.

44
00:04:38,704 --> 00:04:44,053
Sometimes called the wheel, but that's taken from the Tibetan tradition because they made a nice little picture out of it.

45
00:04:46,677 --> 00:04:59,458
Now, and in the early scriptures, when he's talking, you can see that the discourse, the teaching is not formulated.

46
00:05:00,098 --> 00:05:01,982
Often he just talks about the six links.

47
00:05:02,002 --> 00:05:04,206
Sometimes it's down to even three.

48
00:05:04,877 --> 00:05:14,358
And later on, as he's having to go around and teach, and remember in those days, you know, there's no mobile phones, you can't record anything.

49
00:05:14,939 --> 00:05:20,350
So he's going to have to say the same thing every time somebody asks him.

50
00:05:20,370 --> 00:05:24,017
Everywhere he went, they'd ask him the same question, you see, you know, how do you get liberated?

51
00:05:24,319 --> 00:05:25,401
Here we go again with James.

52
00:05:28,098 --> 00:05:34,894
So as time goes on, he formulates and he comes up with these enormous lists.

53
00:05:35,396 --> 00:05:45,060
There actually are about 300 and odd lists, but we're only concerned with the main ones in this particular teaching of dependent origination.

54
00:05:46,357 --> 00:06:07,891
you want to know all the lists there there's a whole collection of them of course in what's called the numerical sayings and they're all put together according to uh ones like one of these that's nibana two of these three of these and it just goes all the way up to eleven so uh that's there if you want to it's a big thick book you know

55
00:06:09,172 --> 00:06:17,262
So it starts, the beginning of the dependent origination is this word avidya, which is often translated as ignorance.

56
00:06:17,283 --> 00:06:21,949
But that gives it a feeling that you should have known, you know, you shouldn't have been such an idiot.

57
00:06:22,329 --> 00:06:24,673
You should have known what was going to happen.

58
00:06:24,973 --> 00:06:29,699
But actually the word avidya is very simply not knowing, just don't know.

59
00:06:29,759 --> 00:06:38,031
And it's from this don't know that we land in a situation and presume it's quite understandable that this is what we are.

60
00:06:38,011 --> 00:06:45,519
So there we are, we're born and there's that slow awakening through our babyhood and into childhood.

61
00:06:45,920 --> 00:06:47,141
And what do you experience?

62
00:06:47,201 --> 00:06:52,567
You only experience this body, this mind, this relationship with the world.

63
00:06:53,069 --> 00:06:58,113
So it's quite understandable that, you know, you come to the age, a certain age and you say, well, this is me.

64
00:06:58,654 --> 00:06:59,495
This is me, you see.

65
00:07:01,601 --> 00:07:07,208
Now, because of that, we, of course, have a wrong relationship immediately with the world.

66
00:07:07,348 --> 00:07:09,009
So what is that relationship?

67
00:07:09,029 --> 00:07:10,831
Well, I just want to make myself happy.

68
00:07:11,372 --> 00:07:12,754
That's pretty straightforward.

69
00:07:12,834 --> 00:07:14,115
I just want to be happy.

70
00:07:14,755 --> 00:07:18,480
And I find that if I collect a lot of things, I get more and more happy.

71
00:07:19,081 --> 00:07:24,367
I've got lots of money, lots of friends, a good job, two cars and all that sort of stuff.

72
00:07:24,387 --> 00:07:26,209
I feel much more happy.

73
00:07:26,189 --> 00:07:28,454
Yeah, that sort of accumulation.

74
00:07:28,656 --> 00:07:35,754
And sometimes I might be happy reading and listening to music and art and nature and all that sort of stuff.

75
00:07:35,774 --> 00:07:40,247
But all of it is geared upon making me happy because that's all I want to be.

76
00:07:40,267 --> 00:07:41,851
I just want to be happy for heaven's sake.

77
00:07:42,119 --> 00:07:45,766
Now, of course, once you've accumulated, there's the danger that you might lose it.

78
00:07:46,428 --> 00:07:47,812
Hence, protectiveness.

79
00:07:48,052 --> 00:07:49,095
Who are you protecting against?

80
00:07:49,576 --> 00:07:50,959
Well, everybody else.

81
00:07:51,279 --> 00:07:58,456
So you have to create this idea of pushing things away.

82
00:07:58,437 --> 00:08:00,139
And there's your aversion.

83
00:08:00,418 --> 00:08:06,406
And if, of course, what you are dealing with is bigger than you, bigger than me, well, you've got to run for it.

84
00:08:06,887 --> 00:08:17,519
So there you have your basic tripod, you might say, of how we fundamentally react to the world because we've mistaken it to be ourselves.

85
00:08:18,221 --> 00:08:20,884
So acquisitiveness, aversion and fear.

86
00:08:22,096 --> 00:08:25,759
And from there on, of course, we do things.

87
00:08:26,360 --> 00:08:31,084
Sometimes, of course, we do things for other reasons, like out of love, compassion, joy.

88
00:08:31,144 --> 00:08:39,131
But even that slightly tainted, you know, you can know that when you do somebody a good turn and they don't say thank you.

89
00:08:39,413 --> 00:08:40,874
Well, that really hurts, doesn't it?

90
00:08:40,894 --> 00:08:44,356
I mean, you know, you need to be appreciated.

91
00:08:45,097 --> 00:08:49,302
So there's always that little bit of conceit in there somewhere, right?

92
00:08:49,282 --> 00:08:53,206
And so, these three things lead us into actions.

93
00:08:53,246 --> 00:09:00,176
They're actions through thought, we create stories, etc., through what we say, and of course, what we do.

94
00:09:00,917 --> 00:09:12,792
And then, because they come in from an unwholesome base, we have that secondary layer of misery, guilt, shame, remorse, and so on.

95
00:09:12,772 --> 00:09:23,322
So you can see we've entered into a relationship with the world which is causing us to have developed habits that are unwholesome.

96
00:09:23,486 --> 00:09:26,711
And that's what happens in the dependent origination.

97
00:09:27,231 --> 00:09:33,701
Out of this ignorance, we create the delusion, the delusion of me being this human being, a self.

98
00:09:34,663 --> 00:09:37,846
And because of that, I have these habits.

99
00:09:38,488 --> 00:09:46,659
They're known as, in the Pali, it's translated as volitional conditionings, right?

100
00:09:46,679 --> 00:09:48,162
Basically, they're just your habits.

101
00:09:49,879 --> 00:09:54,268
Now, those run underneath everything we're doing.

102
00:09:54,328 --> 00:09:59,457
From the moment you wake up to the moment you fall asleep, they're running there as potential, okay?

103
00:09:59,498 --> 00:10:04,567
This potential of delusion and the potential of unwholesome habits.

104
00:10:04,628 --> 00:10:06,572
And they run over everything, okay?

105
00:10:07,429 --> 00:10:31,631
Now, because of that, so avijja pachya sankara, sankara pachya vijnana, it's because of these arising of these habits provoked, shall we say, by stimulus from the outside, by other people, even by from the habits themselves inside, like you wake up in the morning and you feel really excited about something.

106
00:10:31,611 --> 00:10:39,192
So that initial arising, shall we say, has to manifest.

107
00:10:39,442 --> 00:10:46,910
And what it manifests on is this screen, just like this screen that I'm looking at now with you all sitting there.

108
00:10:47,491 --> 00:10:53,519
It's a screen which is sensitive to information that comes upon it.

109
00:10:54,279 --> 00:10:59,346
And it's always coming from the sense bases, one of which is the mind itself.

110
00:11:00,327 --> 00:11:03,692
So there you have your beginning of every moment.

111
00:11:03,751 --> 00:11:05,313
You have that consciousness.

112
00:11:06,626 --> 00:11:08,293
which is receiving information, right?

113
00:11:08,995 --> 00:11:12,307
So this is not the same as awareness, okay?

114
00:11:12,909 --> 00:11:14,033
It's not the same as awareness.

115
00:11:14,053 --> 00:11:15,077
This is consciousness.

116
00:11:15,097 --> 00:11:17,667
This is what you're aware of, okay?

117
00:11:18,405 --> 00:11:26,395
Now, out of that consciousness, you become aware of, and this is the first deconstruction of the Buddha, the body and mind.

118
00:11:27,197 --> 00:11:32,423
And to make that very clear to ourselves, for those of you who know, that's actually the first insights.

119
00:11:32,823 --> 00:11:43,738
Those are the first insights, to know that we are a compound of physicality and mentality, and that the one is always reacting off the other.

120
00:11:44,409 --> 00:12:01,827
And in our meditation, that's why I keep stressing in the morning, you see, to make that very clear to ourselves, even during the day, to make that very clear to ourselves, that if I'm going to open a door and I'm standing there, there's an intention, that's mentality, intention, intention.

121
00:12:02,408 --> 00:12:05,251
And then I empower the intention and the hand moves.

122
00:12:05,572 --> 00:12:08,274
So the hand is, of course, physicality.

123
00:12:08,254 --> 00:12:14,668
When I touch the door handle, what I'm getting are sensations from the physical nature.

124
00:12:15,109 --> 00:12:22,504
But it's the mind that actually experiences it as either cold or warm and so on and so forth.

125
00:12:22,524 --> 00:12:27,495
All you're getting from your fingertips or your hand are just physical sensations.

126
00:12:28,960 --> 00:12:43,323
And it's beginning to undo these things, undo that process, which is slowly deconstructing this idea that I am an integer, that I am a one, that I am whole, entire.

127
00:12:44,299 --> 00:12:52,554
Now, because of this body and mind, nāma rūpa pācchā salayatana.

128
00:12:52,575 --> 00:12:52,956
That's right.

129
00:12:53,255 --> 00:13:00,789
Hold on, I've got to remember it.

130
00:13:00,909 --> 00:13:01,630
Yes, salayatana.

131
00:13:01,951 --> 00:13:08,703
So the salayatana are your six senses dependent on the body and mind.

132
00:13:09,544 --> 00:13:16,192
Now this is important because a consciousness is dependent on one of these six senses, right?

133
00:13:16,312 --> 00:13:19,657
You can't have a consciousness that mixes them both.

134
00:13:20,418 --> 00:13:29,269
Now it feels that way, you know, like you're at home and you're watching TV and you're having a coffee and biscuit or something, and it seems all one.

135
00:13:29,328 --> 00:13:34,134
You're watching, you're hearing, you're tasting, and it's all heavenly.

136
00:13:34,115 --> 00:13:40,726
But actually in Buddhist psychology these are all very separate consciousnesses just running one after the other.

137
00:13:41,389 --> 00:13:48,181
A bit like the old film really where you get 26 frames per second or something.

138
00:13:48,982 --> 00:13:52,950
And that gives you the illusion of continuity.

139
00:13:55,376 --> 00:13:59,962
So those are your six sense bases, and the sixth, of course, is the mind.

140
00:14:00,484 --> 00:14:07,793
Actually, it's all mind because, of course, the contact, which is the next point, see?

141
00:14:07,812 --> 00:14:10,596
Because of these six senses, we have contact.

142
00:14:11,076 --> 00:14:17,706
The contact is the point where the sense base touches upon the object.

143
00:14:17,686 --> 00:14:39,288
so the physical base is you know the base of touch is straightforward i mean if my hands touch each other that point of contact is my primary percept now that's still coming into the mind you see still coming into the mind uh in the at the ear for instance the primary

144
00:14:39,606 --> 00:15:09,410
percept that comes in the primary information that comes in is just pressure it's just pressure right you can actually experience that and it's only when it's taken into the mind that it creates an actual sound right so uh it's the same with with with uh seeing um oh dear there's a there's a book by um uh this american teacher i can't remember her name now it'll come to me all of a sudden

145
00:15:09,695 --> 00:15:13,360
And I think it's called Insight, something like that.

146
00:15:13,400 --> 00:15:15,484
And she's a Mahasi practitioner.

147
00:15:15,543 --> 00:15:18,568
Actually, she died quite young from brain cancer, for heaven's sake.

148
00:15:19,429 --> 00:15:26,640
But her insight was how what she was seeing that just broke up into millions of pixels.

149
00:15:27,702 --> 00:15:30,988
And when you think about it, that's exactly what's there on the retina.

150
00:15:31,107 --> 00:15:36,596
All you've got are these little endings of nerves which are sensitive to light.

151
00:15:36,947 --> 00:15:44,240
And from that she saw how that information is taken into the mind and created into an image.

152
00:15:46,364 --> 00:15:48,548
So that's the point of contact.

153
00:15:48,567 --> 00:15:49,610
It's very, very basic.

154
00:15:50,231 --> 00:15:58,047
And that's what I'm really trying to drive you towards when I say at breakfast, drive your attention into your tongue, right?

155
00:15:58,106 --> 00:16:07,164
To get right down to tasting before you give it a name, before you have any idea of what it is that you're actually tasting.

156
00:16:07,726 --> 00:16:07,966
Okay?

157
00:16:10,174 --> 00:16:11,456
And that's the point of contact.

158
00:16:11,476 --> 00:16:33,870
Now, at the next level, when it's finally produced a feeling of some sort, a sensation of some sort, then you have that judgmental, judicious, should we say, judicious moment where you realize that something is either painful or pleasurable.

159
00:16:34,254 --> 00:16:41,428
So everything that we experience has to be on that line.

160
00:16:41,789 --> 00:16:46,879
It's either very, very pleasurable, moving towards neutral, or very, very painful.

161
00:16:46,960 --> 00:16:47,259
That's it.

162
00:16:47,400 --> 00:16:51,589
Everything we experience, you'll be able to put somewhere on that line.

163
00:16:52,330 --> 00:16:54,293
And that's the duality that we live in.

164
00:16:54,374 --> 00:16:56,398
You can't overcome that.

165
00:16:56,513 --> 00:17:03,960
Whatever we perceive, whatever we feel, whatever we experience as pleasant will remain so.

166
00:17:04,079 --> 00:17:06,942
You can't get rid of that experience.

167
00:17:06,962 --> 00:17:08,064
You can't wash it out.

168
00:17:08,904 --> 00:17:12,848
And the same, of course, is true with something that's unpleasant.

169
00:17:13,148 --> 00:17:18,595
Feeling, emotions, unpleasant thinking, unpleasant thoughts that come to the mind, etc.

170
00:17:20,757 --> 00:17:24,039
So that's the point of vedana, feeling.

171
00:17:24,188 --> 00:17:30,642
And it's at this point that this underlying business begins to manifest.

172
00:17:30,662 --> 00:17:38,619
So remember, so underlying, we've got this ignorance, this not knowing, this delusion, and all these little habits that we have.

173
00:17:39,005 --> 00:17:40,888
And so in comes this contact.

174
00:17:41,289 --> 00:17:44,376
So we're walking down the street and we see something.

175
00:17:44,458 --> 00:17:45,599
Well, not these days.

176
00:17:45,640 --> 00:17:46,602
We don't go shopping anymore.

177
00:17:48,646 --> 00:17:55,983
You're on the screen and it comes up with this thing that you're looking for, a new whatever.

178
00:17:55,963 --> 00:18:18,646
a new mobile and it shoots up on the screen you see and immediately you get this you get this little movement from a habit which is not only to do with all the stuff that you know about mobile it's also to do with oh i'd like that right so there's your there's your tanha there's your desire

179
00:18:18,626 --> 00:18:28,771
And now this desire remember is coming out of that fundamental delusion of seeking happiness in the sensual world.

180
00:18:30,862 --> 00:18:37,849
And what happens is, of course, that happiness that we have becomes dependent on what it is that we own.

181
00:18:37,890 --> 00:18:39,231
There's your problem.

182
00:18:39,732 --> 00:18:46,180
So you take away what it is that you own and misery arises, a sense of loss.

183
00:18:46,279 --> 00:18:49,344
It can be very little, of course, but it can also be quite great.

184
00:18:49,743 --> 00:18:56,952
And when you extend this to relationship with people, it can be awfully full of grief.

185
00:18:58,402 --> 00:19:23,480
So that business of tanha is a way of relating to something whereby whatever mental state we are enjoying or not enjoying, aversion, fear, all those sorts of things, is dependent on something, depending on something over which I don't actually have control.

186
00:19:23,900 --> 00:19:49,484
so it's uh it's not a brilliant situation to get ourselves into but that's basically about 90 of our lives so i was saying this morning that there was uh there's only a few of us of us here uh that you know there's this danger with climate change that there won't be any more tea well you can imagine i mean that's absolute disaster you know it takes away the will to live so so

187
00:19:49,464 --> 00:19:56,212
So that sort of dependency on tea, coffee, drinks, biscuits and all that, they're only very minor.

188
00:19:56,534 --> 00:20:16,538
But when you don't get it, you realize how much of your present happiness, the bit that was feeling bored and using it to escape from boredom or escape from a bit of depression, how you've lifted yourself out by attaching to something which is going to create a pleasant mental state.

189
00:20:17,699 --> 00:20:18,240
Okay?

190
00:20:18,692 --> 00:20:20,335
So this is tanha.

191
00:20:20,355 --> 00:20:21,076
That's this.

192
00:20:21,096 --> 00:20:24,579
And of course, the Buddha points to this as the crucial point.

193
00:20:25,039 --> 00:20:26,301
And it's the point of escape.

194
00:20:26,541 --> 00:20:31,106
That's the point of escape from this delusion.

195
00:20:31,166 --> 00:20:35,192
It's to catch those desires and allow them to burn out.

196
00:20:35,971 --> 00:20:45,442
And that eventually undermines the habit and it doesn't... See, this is the interesting thing that we'll come back to Me Chi Kiao.

197
00:20:46,282 --> 00:20:52,111
It doesn't actually destroy them, but it destroys their power over us.

198
00:20:52,131 --> 00:20:52,991
I'll come back to that in a minute.

199
00:20:53,813 --> 00:21:03,726
So once we understand that we've got to be absolutely aware, we've got to be attentive to the arising of desires.

200
00:21:04,507 --> 00:21:11,615
And it's very difficult unless we're in a very calm state, unless we're actually not rushing, we're not caught up in something.

201
00:21:12,372 --> 00:21:23,833
